{
    "analysis": "We have summarized the available metric and trace data (metric.csv: 91,109 rows across 56 cmdb_ids spanning 2020-05-26T03:30 to 2020-05-26T04:30+08; trace.csv: 5,520 rows across 9 cmdb_ids spanning 04:00–04:29+08). Next we must follow preprocess -> anomaly detection -> fault identification -> root cause localization. The immediate next analysis step is to compute global thresholds (P95 and P5) for every component-KPI using the full metric series, then restrict to the incident time window (May 26, 2020 04:00 to 04:30, UTC+8) and detect anomalies per component-KPI. From that we will get the top candidate component-KPIs with earliest anomaly timestamps and severity to narrow down which components to investigate with traces/logs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) calculate global P95 and global P5 using the full available series for that component-KPI. Then filter metric rows to the incident window from '2020-05-26 04:00:00+08:00' to '2020-05-26 04:30:00+08:00' (inclusive). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) present in the window, compute: total points in window, number of points > global P95 (anomalies_high), number of points < global P5 (anomalies_low), earliest timestamp of any anomaly (either direction), max value in window, min value in window. Return a compact table of the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) sorted by (anomalies_high + anomalies_low) descending. For ties sort by earliest anomaly timestamp ascending. Also return the full list of unique cmdb_ids that appear in these top 20. Limit all outputs to these aggregates only." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We previously computed global P95 and P5 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using full metric series, filtered the metrics to the incident window 2020-05-26 04:00:00+08:00 to 2020-05-26 04:30:00+08:00, and produced a top-20 list of (cmdb_id,kpi_name) series with anomaly counts. Each top series (~30 points) showed 3 points above P95 and 3 points below P5; the earliest anomalies among them begin between 04:00 and 04:12+08. The top candidate components are 11 cmdb_ids (os_017, os_020, redis_011, db_013, redis_005, os_019, os_010, db_007, os_002, os_009, os_022). This indicates multiple OS/Redis/DB KPIs had both high and low outliers in the incident window. We now need to identify actual 'fault' subsequences (consecutive anomaly points) per candidate component-KPI, filter out isolated spikes, compute their start time and severity (breach relative to threshold) to narrow root-cause candidates and prepare for trace analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the previously returned top-20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) series, detect faults in the incident window 2020-05-26 04:00:00+08:00 to 2020-05-26 04:30:00+08:00 as follows:\n1) Reuse the global P95 and P5 computed from the full series for each component-KPI. 2) Mark each point in the window as: HIGH_ANOMALY if value > P95, LOW_ANOMALY if value < P5, else NORMAL. 3) Identify consecutive runs (contiguous timestamps) of HIGH_ANOMALY and of LOW_ANOMALY as candidate faults. 4) For each candidate fault produce one row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_type (HIGH/LOW), fault_start_ts (earliest point), fault_end_ts (latest point), point_count (length), max_value_in_fault, min_value_in_fault, global_threshold_used (P95 for HIGH, P5 for LOW), breach_ratio = (max_value - P95)/P95 for HIGH or (P5 - min_value)/P5 for LOW (report as positive number). 5) Filter out candidate faults whose breach_ratio <= 0.5 (i.e., <=50% breach) as likely false positives. 6) Return the resulting fault table limited to top 20 rows sorted by fault_start_ts ascending. Also return a compact aggregate: counts of faults per cmdb_id (for cmdb_ids present in the returned faults). Keep outputs compact and textual only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We identified 3 validated faults from metric analysis within the incident window: a single-point HIGH fault on redis_011.instantaneous_input_kbps at 2020-05-26T04:00:00+08:00 (breach_ratio=0.839), a 3-point LOW fault on os_010.Processor_load_1_min at 04:12–04:14 (breach_ratio=0.792), and a 3-point LOW fault on os_017.Disk_avgqu_sz at 04:17–04:19 (breach_ratio=0.520). These faults span different component levels (redis service vs OS nodes). According to the rules, when faults exist at different levels for a single failure, the root-cause level should be the one with the most significant deviation from its threshold (>>50%). Redis_011’s breach_ratio is the highest (0.839), and it also has the earliest anomaly (04:00). Before finalizing the root cause component and reason, we should confirm whether traces show redis_011 participating in affected call chains (i.e., whether redis is downstream/faulty in traces) and whether traces indicate propagation or errors related to redis. Currently trace.csv’s cmdb_id list from earlier summary did not show redis_011, so we must check whether any traces reference redis_011 or otherwise link the identified OS faults to redis. This will help confirm if redis_011 is indeed the root cause or if an OS-level fault propagated or caused separate failures.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv and filter to the incident window 2020-05-26 04:00:00+08:00 through 2020-05-26 04:30:00+08:00. For each of the three fault cmdb_ids ['redis_011','os_010','os_017'] compute compact aggregates: total trace rows in window for that cmdb_id, earliest and latest trace timestamp in window, and top up to 10 trace_name values with their row counts (sorted by count desc). Additionally, search the entire filtered trace set for any trace_name or any row that contains the substring 'redis' (case-insensitive) and return up to 20 matching rows with columns (timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value). Return all outputs as compact textual tables only." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We found 3 metric-derived faults: redis_011 (HIGH single-point at 2020-05-26T04:00:00+08:00, breach_ratio=0.839), os_010 (LOW multi-point 04:12–04:14, breach_ratio=0.792), and os_017 (LOW multi-point 04:17–04:19, breach_ratio=0.520). Trace data contains no records for these three components in the incident window, and a search for 'redis' in traces returned no matches. Given lack of trace corroboration, we must rely on metrics to confirm whether redis_011 is a credible root-cause (it has the largest breach and earliest anomaly) or whether it is an isolated spike. Next, we should examine all metrics for redis_011 (global thresholds and incident-window behavior) to see if multiple redis KPIs are anomalous concurrently or if the instantaneous_input_kbps spike is isolated.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Analyze all metric KPIs for cmdb_id 'redis_011'. For each kpi_name belonging to redis_011 compute using the full available series: count_full, global_P95, global_P5. Then filter to the incident window '2020-05-26 04:00:00+08:00' through '2020-05-26 04:30:00+08:00' and compute: count_window, anomalies_high (points > P95), anomalies_low (points < P5), earliest_anomaly_ts (if any), max_value_window, min_value_window. Return a compact table sorted by (anomalies_high + anomalies_low) desc (limit 20 rows). Additionally, return the raw (timestamp, value) rows in the incident window for redis_011 and kpi_name 'instantaneous_input_kbps' (limit up to 30 rows), and include the P95 and P5 used for that KPI. Keep outputs compact and textual only."
}

